# Homepage First Workflow

## For Existing Brands

Skip to **Step 3**. The Design DNA and design tokens are already established. Build new pages using the brand's registered axis choices, established section primitives, and brand-specific rules.

## For New Brands — Full Sequence

### Step 1 — Design DNA Intake

Run the `new-brand-prototype` skill. Do not write any component code until this is complete. The skill guides through:

- Choosing all 8 Design DNA axes (checked against the registry in `platform-premium-art-direction`)
- Researching reference screens via Refero MCP
- Defining the full design token set (colors, fonts, spacing, CTA shape, section padding, content width)
- Generating the first hero and content images

### Step 2 — Design Preview Page

Build `src/app/design-preview/page.tsx` as the first deliverable. This page is the visual contract for the brand and must include:

- Color palette swatches with hex values for every token
- Typography scale: h1, h2, h3, body, caption, label — using the approved font stack
- CTA button variants: primary, secondary, ghost
- Hero section preview using the approved images and background archetype
- Two sample content sections showing the section rhythm and spacing

**Stop here and get explicit user approval before building the homepage.**

### Step 3 — Homepage Build

The homepage is the source of truth for all visual patterns. Apply all 8 registered Design DNA choices consistently. Decompose into named section components under `src/views/home/components/` (not inline in `page.tsx`).

Validate before moving to interior pages:
- Mobile-first responsiveness (test at 375px, 768px, 1280px)
- LCP hero image/video is optimized and loads fast
- Accessibility: heading hierarchy, focus states, color contrast
- Trust clarity: a first-time visitor understands who this is for within 5 seconds

### Step 4 — Interior Pages

Extend from homepage primitives. Every interior page must:

- Use the same section wrapper pattern, spacing scale, and typography from the homepage
- Not introduce new color families, font families, or layout archetypes
- Reference the registered Design DNA if any visual ambiguity arises during build
